# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The code aims to generate all possible permutations of a given set of numbers.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The code uses a recursive backtracking approach to generate all the permutations. It starts by fixing the first element of the permutation and then recursively generates the permutations for the remaining elements by swapping the first element with each of the subsequent elements. This process continues until all elements have been considered as the first element.

> Inside the 'solve' function:
-  It checks if 'ind' is equal to the size of 'nums'. If it is, that means we have formed one permutation, so it adds 'nums' to the 'res' vector and returns from the function.
-  Otherwise, it enters a loop starting from the current 'ind' up to the end of the 'nums' vector
- Inside the loop, it swaps the elements at 'ind' and 'i' indices to try different possibilities for the first element.
-  After swapping, it makes a recursive call to 'solve' with 'ind+1' (moving to the next index) to generate permutations for the remaining elements.

`Let's analyze the time complexity of the code. For each element at index 'ind', there are 'n - ind' choices to be made for swapping (where 'n' is the total number of elements). Then, for each choice, we make a recursive call to generate permutations for the remaining elements. Therefore, the time complexity of this algorithm can be expressed as O(n * n!), where 'n' is the number of elements in the input vector 'nums'.`



# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(n*n!)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
