solutions.content:
Top discussion section is filled with Double Linked List 
so I thought I'll put another way to solve this problem up here.

The solution scales with O(N + M) amortized time and space 
where N and M are  `get` and  `put` calls respectively. 
It is a fast solution as well. The idea is to push all calls into a queue 
and count how many times same keys appear in the queue. 
If certain keys counts are zero then they are removed from the hashmap.

```
unordered_map <int, int> m, cnt;
queue <int> q;
int n;
LRUCache(int capacity) : n(capacity) {}
int get(int key) {
	if (cnt.find(key) == cnt.end()) 
		return -1;
	q.push(key);
	cnt[key]++;
	return m[key];
}
void put(int key, int value) {
	q.push(key);
	cnt[key]++;
	m[key] = value;
	while (cnt.size() > n) {
		int cur = q.front(); q.pop();
		if (cnt[cur]-- == 1) 
			cnt.erase(cur);
	}
}
```

With regards to the most popular solution of Double Linked List: 
that solution scales with O(C) for space, which is less than number of all calls. 
`C = capacity = 3000 < N + M = 2*10^5 calls` so it is a much better 
spacewise solution, but it is much harder to write I think.

