Going to simplify the example to focus on the relevant calls:
Put(1,1)
Put(2,2)
Get(1)
Put(3,3)

**NOTE**: Order is from Most Recently Used (MRU) to Least Recently Used (LRU)

`Put(1,1)`: Puts (1,1) into the cache (fresh entry; did not already exist). Cache: { (1,1) }

`Put(2,2)`: Puts (2,2) into the cache (fresh entry; did not already exist). Cache: { (2,2), (1,1) }

`Get(1)`: Gets the value associated with key `1` (which is also `1`). Cache: { (1,1), (2,2) }
**Notice that (1,1) was moved to the front as it is now the MRU**.

`Put(3,3)`: Puts (3,3) into the cache (fresh entry; did not already exist).
Cache (BEFORE eviction): { (3,3), (1,1), (2,2) }
Cache (AFTER eviction): { (3,3), (1,1) }

So, to answer your question, the reason `2` is ejected before `1` is due to the `Get(1)` call. It's not defined explicitly in the problem but **both** `Get` and `Put` cause the ordering to change.

